node.text: Today's #GoogleDoodle encourages you to look up at the stars. Head to our homepage to see photos from @NASA's James Webb Space Telescope, including the deepest infrared photo of the universe ever taken 🤯 These awe-inspiring images will help astronomers study every phase of cosmic history, which spans a massive 13.5 billion years, and the mysteries beyond our galaxy.

node.text:
“Pictures tell us about the world, so it’s important that they do that with a sense of accuracy and beauty that maps back to our real experiences.” — Florian Koenigsberger 

Florian leads our Image Equity Initiative, helping to make sure Pixel cameras capture everyone as they truly are. Learn more about our efforts to build a world where everyone belongs at the link in bio.

node.text: This #TeacherAppreciationWeek and every week we're thankful for all the educators helping future generations grow. Tap the link in bio to hear @CCSSO National Teacher Of The Year’s Kurt Russell share his story, the importance of the teaching community and ways we're showing.

node.text: "After it became clear that Live Transcribe helps me to communicate, it became clear that we could extend it to help others,” Googler Dimitri Kanevsky says about his work as a speech research scientist. He’s developing technology like Live Transcribe to help people fully participate in the conversations around them. Learn more about our efforts to build a world where everyone belongs at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Magnifying glass with 4 Google colors. Text reads: "7 updates from Google I/O"

node.text: First look at the Google #PixelFold 😍 #GoogleIO #FixedOnPixel

node.accessibility_caption: An image of Firefall with text that reads "Pixel" and "4 Pixel photography tips I used to capture pictures of Firefall"

node.text: Back in February, one Googler had the chance to capture Firefall, a natural phenomenon in California where the setting sun makes a famous waterfall look like a lava flow. To get the best pics possible, she asked the @googlepixel camera team for pointers — then grabbed her #Pixel7 Pro and made it happen. 📸🔥 Tap the link in bio to learn more about the tips that helped her take and edit some of her favorite Firefall photos.

node.accessibility_caption: An image of Firefall with text that reads "Pixel" and "4 Pixel photography tips I used to capture pictures of Firefall"
Two side-by-side images of Firefall. The left image is much more zoomed out than on the right. Text reads "To get my shots, I replied on Pixel 7 Pro's Super Res Zoom, which can shoot up to 30x."

Two side by side images of Firefall. The image on the left has people, who do not appear in the image on the right. Text says "With a quick little tap here and a swipe there, all the extra distractions disappeared, thanks to Magic Eraser."

Two side by side images of Firefall. The image on the left is more golden in color, where the water is bright red in the image on the right. Text reads "Using the Shadow and Brightness sliders helped me adjust to how Firefall's colors changed from Friday (left) to Sunday."

An image of snow surrounding a waterfall, with the water looking slightly blurred, as if in motion. Text reads "Pixel's Long Exposure mode showed what was moving while everything else was crisp, like fast-flowing waterfalls (perfect!)."

node.text: Today’s #GoogleDoodle kicks off Teacher Appreciation Week and celebrates the teachers who planted the seeds of knowledge and curiosity in our lives. 🌱🌼
